{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_flash_ver01/data/sn87062224/00514156736/1949061701/0381.xml":{"full_text":"MILFORD CHRONICLE\nESTABLISHED OCTOBER 4. 1878\n\nTHEO. TOWNSEND\nEditor and Proprietor from 1878 to 1910\nMILFORD CHRONICLE PUBLISHING COMPANY\n10 TO 1\u00ab SOUTH WEST FRONT STREET\nMILFORD. DELAWARE\nPUBLISHERS\n_!-President\n_Vlce-Pre\u00abident\n.Secretary-Treasurer\n3. Marshall Townsend.\nVirginia S. Townsend.\nTheodore Townsend\n_Editor\n.Managing Editor\nQ. Marshall Townsend.\nRobert H. Yerkee\nBzclualve National Advertising Representative\nGreater Weeklies\nMew Turk Chicago Detroit Philadelphia\nSubscription Terms\nMs\u00bb\u2014In Delaware, *3.00 1\na Tear\nOutside of Delaware. *3.00 a Tear\nBy\nJive Cent\u00ab\nSingle Copies.\n_\nDELAWARE'S leading weekly NEWSPAPER\nnewspaper\u2014bothPin^ize *of paper? number o^pailes printed\nvolume of new* carried, and lineage of adv\u00eartising pre\n\u25a0en ted each Issue. All advertising Is sold on a basis of a\nguaranteed circulation of over 7,000 copies each issue,\n\u2022PHONES: 19 and 20\u2014MILFORD\nAddress all communications to the Milford Chronicle\nPublishing Company, Milford, Delaware\nRetend u second-class matter March 3, 1*7* at the\npoetofflca at Milford, Del., under Act of March 3,1*7*\n\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nThe Associated Press is entitled exclusively \\o the use\ntor republication of all the local news printed in this nevra\npaper, as well as all AP news dispatches\nFRIDAY, JUNE 17, 1949\nWHEAT IS CIVILIZATION\nIt has been said that \"wheat is civiliza\ntion.\" Much of the history of the world has\nbeen determined by whether grain crops\nwere good or bad. War, pestilence and fam\nine have all followed the failure of plantings.\nThis country is one of the largest gram pro\nducers, and the quality of each year's crop\nhas a very direct bearing on the prosperity of\nagriculture and the national welfare as a\nwhole. But grain in the fields has small value.\nIt must be moved to the elevators at the\nmajor terminals and to the various centers\nwhere it is processed and turned into usable\nproducts. This year, moving the grain pre\nsents an additional problem. Until recently,\n300,000 carloads of last year's crop was held\nin storage under government loans. That\nhad to be moved before the beginning of the\nnew harvest, to make space. What agency of\ntransportation can perform, swiftly, effi\nciently and economically, the big task of\nhandling the wheat, barley, oats, corn and the\nrest? The only answer is, the railroads. The\nother carriers, valuable as they are in cer\ntain fields, just haven't the capacity. When\nit comes to mass transportation\u2014the kind of\ntransportation on which our industrial and,\nagricultural economies rest\u2014the iron horse\nis still supreme. The grain crop is on the\nmove\u2014and it's moving on rails.\nT?TT?T? TM TUF TrnDP'C'TC!\nFIRE IN THE FORESTS\nSummer and fall constitute two of the\nmost serious fire ueriods in this ronntrv\nmost serious nre periods in mis country.\nforests and fields dry out, awaiting only the\ntouch of a spark to burst into flame. Tour\nists throng the highways. Thousands of\ncampers go into the woods. Commercial\ncamps and vacation spots Of all kinds run at\ncapacity. Every year sees the destruction\nby a\ntragic toll Of Wildlife. Some forest fires do\noccur spontaneously, from lightning or other\nli natural causes. But a far greater number\ncan be attributed to human carelessness and\n&W X throws burn\nand the camper who lives'! to without\nearth n untii OTery^pto is^ut\np otect a heritage which, once destroyed,\nmay take centuries to replace. The various\noublie and orivatp bf>dip\u00abs which Hp\u00bb] with\nfire are doimr I finP ioh Tht ^P IS!\ning organizations. But they do little\nI\nII\n1\nI\nI\ni\nwithout public coooeration A forest firp\nS? a\nBUSINESS SLUMP T<* PFATTY HFRF\nBUMWfcfcb bLUMP IS REALLY HERE\nThe slump in business has been made offi\ncial. This happened when Dr. Edwin Nourse,\ntop economic advisor to the President,\nported that the Federal Reserve Board's in\ndustrial production index had dropped to the\nS\u00ee\" of 1947. Dr. Nourse,\nX regarded as a conserva\ntive in his economic views, urged the Presi\ndent to hold down Federal spending, and to\ngo easy on urging increases in taxation. The\ncountry, at this time, is in the middle of a\nWpr^nHppc f \u20acI ho dmg ut or\nrSo?' sellers trying to avoid price\npu s ov mg m one line a Su r\nfnrp^ai' \u00c4\u00c4LP\u00c4 wa f. goes ol l- 1\nthp^pnpraf^tp^p^^K 116 1 \u00b0\u00cek 949\nppS\u00c6idw ihn mlf e W1 k*.,. 15 per\nthan \u00abO nTv stlll J\u00ce\u00ae re\n19 9 fig 11 When\nr nced pric s ncG ag f 1R\net \u00e0 fo r goods 18 expected\nmove ahead. If\npiiov^w Fu S t0 be the c rr ect one, it is\nj\u00ae cu rrent slump is not the begin\n'F a ^Pression. It is, instead, an ad\nKolT! a boom condition which was\nbased on a tenuous foundation. When the\n6 ha( j 66 foUr years\nreasmg shortages and the war-enforced\ncash savings of the people were at an all\ntime high. The inevitable result was a buy\ning spree that took in practically every kind\nof commodity, no matter how high the price\nor how poor the quality. Much of the money\nhas now been spent, the shortages have al\nmost all been made up, the national income is\ndown frorn the peak, and the spending spree\nhas cope to an end. During the course of\nthe adjustment, the attitude of labor will be\nimportant\u2014the cost of labor is a dominant\nfactor in determining the selling price of the\nbulk ot commodities. Some labor groups are\nre\nI\n1\nhow working for increased pay, but this is\nnot universal by any means. A number of\nthe top union officials are displaying con\nsiderable caution. In some lines, it is report\ned that productivity per manhour has been\nrising\u2014when business slackens workers na\nturally put out more effort in order to keep\ntheir jobs. Also, the fairly substantial lay\noffs that have taken place in major industry\nhave largely been confined to the least effi\ncient workers, and the better men have re\nmained on the job. Thus, labor costs may\ndiminish in various fields, even though wage\nrates remain at high levels. All in all, busi\nness trends are being watched with extreme\ncare in all quarters. But there is little real\npessimism.\nSPRAYING FOR PESTS AVAILABLE\nA news article in this week's issue of the\nChronicle carries the information that the\nState Farm Bureau is making available to\npersons in all parts of Delaware a valuable\nspraying service against insect pests. Ac\ncording to this news release machinery and\nexperienced crews are available to spray\nT __\nhomes, gardens and lawns against the Jap\nanese Beetles, ticks which carry Rocky Moun\ntain Fever and other pests. The charge, ac\ncording to the news story, averages for the\nsmall home about $3.00. The charge, of\ncourse, will vary for larger units. This\nservice is needed, is worth-while, and now is\nthe time to do it. This is a worthy project\nfor one or all of the local service clubs to\nsponsor. The application now may elimi\nnate deadly disease carrying flies later. Why\nnot give it thought?\nxjTTLE DELAWARE LEADS THE WAY\nWe wonder whether Delawareans real\nize that within the borders of our little Dia\nmond State is located one of the world s\noutstanding institutions? Frankly we had\nnever given the mental hospital at Farn\nhurst and the Bacon Health Center, which\nnow unit, credit for being than\nan average hospital for the treatment of\nmental cases. In conversation with one of\nthe Nation's outstanding psychiatrists on\nMonday we learned with astonishment just\nwhere Farnhurst really rates in the scheme\nof things. This noted psychiatrist said with\nout reservation that Delaware, under the\nguidance of Dr. Tarumianz, leads the world\nin mental treatment. He dwelt at lengthen\nthe forward steps taken in psychiatric work\nat Farnhurst, he lauded Dr. \"T\", as he is so\nwell known by Delawareans, and emphasiz\ned the outstanding work that is being done\nthere. This may be the opinion of one out\nstanding man in his profession, but his state\n.ment that when psychiatrists gather in con\nference, Delaware methods are sought after\nand given first consideration makes his rea\nSOning forceful. Delawareans may well be\nproud of the mental hospital at Farnhurst\n\u2014and Dr Traumianz is to bo conoratulatpd\nj u j aun anz 18 10 congratulated\nand honored fc.r his years of effort to make\nhis \"hobby\" the center of world interest for\npsychiatrists.\n\nDANGER AT THE GRASSROOTS r\nThe rea j dan g er j n the U. S. today lies not\nin Washington, but at tL grassroots Gov\nernments have always tended to usurp more\nand morp nowpv iintn HiPmeplvoc In avow\nZ an ization there is tTe s\u0153d of tvrannv\nTha\u00c2 X eternal^vfgGlance S the nrice of\nliberty The real danyer in the U S iL, with\nthe miills wh\u00f4 ar\u00ea\u00c2k Dem^?acy is\nd by\"'Ikef/VovernmenT \"htos\nth ngs which that ovei nment Cannot deliver\ncuritv bv these nromisps men arp pvebano\ninySeir Itortlw thri^X\u00bbfi\u2122\nliberties, then initiative, theii dig\nmty their herita e as free men for a bunch\n!\"ir?\" ass?\nkickinA/thP\n\nno\nsense in u\ns lse in a ^he government, as if it\nraw? mu\u00e4sswb\ndividuals, by local governments, and by var\nj ous rou P 8 a seeking special favors and\nbenefits. This represents the \"get-something\nfor-nothing\" psychology in its worst form.\nAnd it is exactly the kind of thing which\nstarves freedom and fattens tyranny.\nREMEMBER WHEN?\nRemember when not Yo long ago, some\n0 f the highest officials in the Federal govern\nment were savinc that a reimnr\u00bb\u00abii+inn a-f\nprice Sols and other such stSt j^cket\nMeasures were necessary if runaway 3 price\nin fl at ion was to be prevented? Do you also\nremember that, at about the same time, the\nsame high officials were dolefully predicting\nthat an y cut in taxes would also give price\ninflation a new shot in the arm and send the\nindexes booming into the stratosphere? We\nali know what happened. Luckily for the\nwelfare of the nation, Congress refused to\nreimpose wartime controls. Congress also\nput a reduction in income taxes into effect.\nFor a considerable period of time the price\nlevel changed relatively little\u2014the big infla\ntionary trend that was forecast didn't appear,\nThen, a few months ago, prices started down\nThey are still going down. In some cases,\nthe drops have been very substantial. Meat\ni s the best example of this. Declines of 20\nper cent-and more in meat prices have been\nregistered since last year's peak. This .was\nthe result of the traditional functioning of\nthe free market. Instead of having a black\nmarket\u2014which always flourishes under gov\neminent controls\u2014we have had a market\nwhich is responsive to the all-powerful forces\nof supply and demand. It is true that the\ntax cuts gave more people more money to\nspend. Along with that, producers in many\nfields increased their output. Prices found\ntheir proper level\u2014as they will continue to\ndo in the future. The advocates of a regi\nmented economy offer interesting theories_\nbut the hard facts just don't back them\nup.\nGETTING TO THE BOTTOM OF IT\nM\nRECORDS/\nOFTHE 1\n'REP\ntriauII\nit\nS\"\nISSSf\n\nvy.tHt\np U3Uc.\nE\nVa Joh ,r \u00ee S'': 1 n k Commissioner ot Education Ar- Announcement has been made ol\nthur R s P aid was appointed under the following appointments by gov\nJohn E Hearn ew School Cod\u00ae by the te ernor Townsend of members of the\nfeif Thlf waf dTnl a? a meeting Sp c l a l District *j cho01 Boa rds\nt f J as d at t which have accepted the provisions\nMrs. Charles Q. Heusted and held last week and at the same of the new school code: Laurel, M.\ndaughter Miss Betty, have return-1 time it was decided to appoint as E Culver, James O. Adams, H. F.\ned home after a two weeks visit his assistant, John Shilling, who Wolfe; Milford, W. G. Abbott, w.\nwith her Parents, Mr. and Mrs. J. was the superintendent of the Kent I Y Sipple, Rev. Henry L. Bunstein;\nW. Hall. iCounty Public Schools. This leaves Dover, James Hall Anderson, Wil\nT \u00c4 SSf \u00ab\u00c4T. \u00c4\u00c4Crafd\u00c4\nPhiladelphia are being entertained a PP llcants which have already have as yet certified to the Gover\nThis\" week^ f nor acceptance of the new code\nMrs. william n. Dorsey on North I Ed ca th,s week 1\nM/alnut street.\n\nj\ny\nCongressman C. R. Layton has\nintroduced a bill in the House to\nmake provisions for the placing of\na German cannon in the George\ntown Public Square, a memorial to\nhis nephew, Lieutenant Lawrence\nare visiting Mrs. Weinmann's par-1 with for this year and it has been L\nenis. Mr. and Mrs. James H. Hill-i a very short crop compared with g\u2122 Tr^ JS5S the\u00f6ennt\nmaU other years border on July 18. last year.\nAs Taken From The Files\nOf The Milford Chronicle\nThirty Years Ago\nMrs. Rose Emory and two daugh\nters have returned home from a\nten-day visit in Laurel and Sea\nford.\nThe Misses Gertrude and Ellen\nMcCullough are spending this week\nwith relatives in Wilmington and\nNew Castle.\nCaptain and Mrs. J. C. Weinmann\nThe pea season is about done\nThe hotels at Bowers were filled\nL. D. Shuman and C. D. Sniggs to their capacity this week-end. A\nColonel and Mrs. William Har-, Paid an official visit to Fort Sauls- part of the guests expect to re\nrison Davis have returned home bury- They were especially inter- main. some time, others only for\nfrom a week's visit to Atlantic ested in the sand which is un- the week-end, but the majority are\nCity, N. J., as the guest of their der the direction of C. D. Stansell. inclined to fishing with hook and\nEdward M. Davis of Wihning- Ve, T soon the y will begin to bury line in the bay. The splendid\nthe magazines under eight feet of catches of late with hook and line\nsand. When completed they will j are bringing the old anglers here\nlook like two huge mounds of sand, j who know the opportunities offer\nThe sand fill wifi soon be in full ed far their success and sport, be\noperution. Foremen McConville side many strangers who have nev\nand Still have done quick work in er visited this place before. It is\nthe laying of the railway. The four a notable occurrence that we see\n\"kinkies\" are little beauties. They j so many automobiles from the near\nwere made for overseas, but come by counties in Pennsylvania as far\nin good for the present operation, j up as Lancaster, also many from\nMrs. Susan Carlisle with her There are about 100 sard cars, well New Jersey and the Eastern Shore\ndaughter, Mrs. Hester O'Brien of made and suited for the job. The of Maryland and Virginia. This\nBuffalo, N. Y., have been visiting enginemen are J. F. Rock, A. B. 1 place is becoming noted for such\nhei niece, Mrs. Darwirt S. Collins Crush and J. C. Nicely\u2014a fine com- j sport and the accessibilities and\nthe facilities offered are always at\nhand for their accommodation.\nson,\nt\u00f6n.\nMrs. J. C. Wharton of Houston\nhas gone to West Chester, Pa., for\nthe commencement where her\ndaughter. Miss Elizabeth, gradu\nates and later they are to take a\ntrip up in New Jersey.\nand other relatives and friends in bination as they \"crush\" the \"rock\nMilford for the past ten days.\nnicely.\ni\nBABSON Discusses 1949 Graduates And lobs\nBABSON PARK, Mass., June\n17\u2014The largest crop ever of col\nlege students will graduate this\nJune from our colleges. In addi\ntion, tens of thousands will grad\nuate from public and private\nhigh schools. There just won't\nbe enough jobs for all.\nNOT ENOUGH JOBS TO\nI GO AROUND\nThe first quarter in 1949 has\nseen increasing cut-backs in la\nbor. Total unemployed now\nnumber nearly three million,\u2014a\nmillion and a half more th\u00e4n a\nyear ago. Some of this unemployment is due to\nseasonal fluctuations. However, an increasing\namount is due to a general slump in sales. Sales\nslumps have backlogged inventories and resulted in\ncut-backs in production\u2014which means fewer jobs.\nMany industries show declines in profits, from\n6.5% in appliances to 37% in textiles, when the first\nquarter of 1949 is compared with the same period\nin 1948. Faced by -this situation, companies are fir\ning, not hiring.\nm\ni\n3\nv\ni\n\nRoger W. Babson\nWHO WILL GET THE JOBS?\nJob competition this season will be rough and\ntough. One out of evtry four college graduates of\nthe class of 1949 will still be job hunting when\nSeptember comes. A young man's character will, in\na real measure, determine whether he gets a job.\nCompanies search out men with strong character\ntraits of integrity, dependability, industriousness,\ningenuity, perseverance, temperance and and a sense\nof responsibility.\n'Companies also book for good personality. Per\nsonality implies flexibility, self-control, emotional\nstability, and the abiility to get along with others.\nBusiness wants thosie with good judgment and com\nmon sense. Businesls wants men with good motiva\ntion, men who have ambition and a purpose, and\nwho are not afraid of hard work. Business wants\nmen who are highly competitive.\nT\n\nSELLING YOURSELF TO A COMPANY\nIn short, then, companies are looking for men\n\nof character, energy and endurance. The power of\nendurance\u2014physical, mental, and spiritual\u2014is the,\nbest foundation 1 know for success. If you have\ndeveloped these traits, and if you can sell yourself j\nin an interview, your chances of getting a job are,\nbetter than average.\nPlan your Job-hunting strategy. With the help!\nof instructors, aptitude tests results, part-time work\nexperiences, personal hobbies, and your classroom\nrecord, decide what you like and what you can do\nbest. Know how you can use your interests, abili\nties, and personality traits productively on a job.\nYou are now ready to direct a carefully prepared\nmail campaign to a hundred or so carefully selected\ncompanies. You will be given the opportunity to in\nterviews if you take the time to write a concise,\nforceful and grammatically correct presentation of\nyourself.\nCan you sell yourself? I know one young man\nwho recently told a prospective employer in the in\nterview: \"Sure, I can sell.\" The interviewer snap\nped back: \"That's fine. I need a new watch. Sell\nme yours!\" Are you prepared for such contingen\ncies? Plan ror them in advance. Talk about the\nPLAN TO MAKE YOURSELF NEEDED\nemployer's needs,\u2014not your needs. Demonstrate to\nthe interviewer that through your part-time job ex\nperiences you have already learned how to work\nand to stick with a job until it is successfully com\npleted. Let him know that you have had the oppor\ntunity to work with people, that you have learned\nhow to get along with them. Show by calling many\ntimes about the job that you have the perserver\nance, self-reliance and industry that he is looking\nfor.\nMake your prospective employer want you. Jobs\nare difficult.to get, but if you really want a job at\ngraduation, you will have one. It has been my life\nphilosophy that you get out of life about what you\nput into it. Confidentially, let me say that those\nof you who come from humble homes with praying\nmothers have the best chance of getting a good job.\nTHC\nHome\nTouin ajg,,\nIN WASHINGTON\nWALTER SH EAO, WNU C*>\ns po n d en t\nSenate to Move\npOR THE FIRST TIME in 135\nX years the senate of the United\nStates, According to present plans, i\nwill hold its sessions outside the j\nCapitol building if and when it i\nmoves lock, stock and barrel, into\nthe swanky, marble-walled, air\nconditioned senate caucus chamber\nin the senate office building about\nJune 30.\nThe occasion of this historic trek\nacross the Capitol grounds is made\nnecessary by the reconstruction of\nthe roofs and the removal of the\nunsightly temporary steel gird\u00e9rs\nand framework in both the house\nand senate chambers.\nThis temporary construction was\nplaced there as a safety measure\nwhen the roofs of th\u00e9 t\u00e9ro Wings\nthreatened to collapse back in 1939\nand 1940.\nDaring that construction pe\nriod, the boose did move oat \u00e9f\nthe ballding and held its sessiona\nin the ways and means chamber\nin the house office boUdlng, bnl\nthe senate remained in the\nCapitol, holding its sessions In\nthe old supreme court chamber\nwhich was vacated by that\njudicial body in 1938 upon the\ncompletion of the new supreme\ncourt building.\n\nThe present house chamber wing\nof the Capitol was completed and\noccupied by the lower body on De\ncember 16, 1857, while the senate\nj chamber was completed two years\ni later and occupied for the first\n1859.\nThe only other occasion when th\u00e9\ncongress held its sessions outside\nthe Capitol building was after the\nburning of the original Capitol by\nthe British on August 24, 1814.\nFrom that time, until the new Cap\nitol building was ready for oc\ncupancy in 1819, Congress met in\nwhat was then Blodgett's hotel at\nSeventh and E streets and later in\na building erected to house them on\na portion of the site now occupied\nby the new supreme court building.\nIn the meantime the beautiful\ngrounds Immediately adjacent to\nthe Capitol on both the house and\nsenate sides resemble a construc\ntion camp with high board walls\nsurrounding temporary buildings\nand quarters for workers.\n\nTardy Budgets\nDuring the 80th Republican-con\ntrolled congress, Democratic lead\ners belabored their Republican\ncolleagues for failure to comply\nwith the congressional reorganiza\ntion act in Setting up a legislative\nbudget by February 15, required\nby the law. And today Democratic\nleaders are smarting under Re\npublican attacks for failure to do\nthe same thing. As a matter of fact,\nwhen the time set for agreeing on\na legislative budget passed, the\nsenate extended the time to May 1.\nThat date has come and gone and\nas yet there has been no budget\nfixed, nor is there likely to be one\nset.\n\nWays of Debate\nAll sorts of extraneous matters\ncreep into debates over appropria\ntion bills. In the floor debate on\nthe post office appropriation meas\nure in the senate the two South\nCarolina senators, Maybank and\nJohnston, wanted to include some\n$170,000 worth of cotton twine, and\nthe battle went on for some hours\nand many pages in the Congression\nal Record;\n\"Senator Maybank\u2014Is It not E\nfact that the United States govern\nment took over the poor cotton\nfarmer and sold it at a profit of\n$90,000,000?\nSenator Taft (Ohio)\u2014Mr.\nPresident, If the senator vriB\nyield I will say that th\u00e9 gov\nernment never got the $90,000,\n000. That was only the figure\nat which it was sold to foreign\ncountries who never paid for\nit. That was the net result of\nlend lease.\n\"Mr. Maybank\u2014But the senator\nwill agree as to the figure; will he\nnot?\n\"Mr. Taft\u2014-Yes; but we got no\nmoney for it. W\u00e9 merely got in re\nturn credits that we canceled. That\nis all we got for it.\n\"Mr. Baiawin (Connecticut)\u2014It\nwas a paper profit of th\u00e9 most\npaperish sort, was it not?\n\"Mr. Taft\u2014That is correct.\n\nSo the department of agriculture\nclaim of a 90-million-doUar profit\nby the CCC on price support for\ncotton is knocked into a cocked hat.\nNo School Curbs\nIn passage of the federal aid to\nschools legislation by the senate,\nthat body decided two fundamental\nquestions which have been moot\nones for the past 30 years: (1) that\nilliteracy is a national problem and\n(2) that federal appropriations for\nschools does not necessarily mean\nfederal control of schools.\nIt has been proved definitely th9t\nfederal aid to education should not\nbe regarded as a levy against the\npeople, but us an investment that\nwill yield large returns.\nAustralian Steel Goes\n'Round And 'Round\nAustraelia is\nexporting steel to England in ex\nchange for tinplate. And Japan is\nexporting steel to Australia be\ncause this country hasn't enough.\nManager, Keth Butler of Broken\nSIDNEY (AP)\n\u00bblift\ny\ni\nH\nSK\nSimplified Government\nT WAS A SIMPLE government\ni 0 f, f or and by the people**\nwhich our forefathers bequeathed\nto thelr p r0 geny, its three branches\nlegislative, administrative, and\njudicial\u2014carried through all units\nfrom the town, through the county\nand state to the federal. It was a\ngovemm\u00e9nt that answered aU the\npurposes of their time, but suc\nceeding generations have so added\nto it that what was simple is now\na complex, scarcely-understandable\ngovernmental machine, in all of\nits various units.\nConditions change from genera\ntion to generation, almost from\nyear to year. Government changes\nin an effort to keep pace with\nchanging 'conditions: Government\nadds to, but never subtracts. New\ndepartments, new bureaus are\nadded, but when conditions no long\n\u00e8r require these additions they are\nhever dropped. In many cases, the\nconditions of half a century ago.\nmore or less, which at the time\nseemed to warrant a new depart\nment or a new bureau for some unit\nof government city, township,\ncounty, state or national\u2014do not\nnow exist.\nThe department or bureau that\nwas added goes on and on, though\nthe need for it has long since\npass\u00e9d, and other expense items,\nadded when it was established, con\ntinue.\nIt is easy to add to our govern\nmental costs, but our political sys\ntem makes it difficult to dispense\nwith those added costs when the\nusefulness of the department or\nbureau is over, il it ever existed.\nEach Job means political patron\nage, and that is something few. if\nany, political party leaders are\nwilling to reduce. That applies to\naU units of government, from that\nof the town through to the national\ngovernment at Washington.\nTwo years ago congress made\na gesture looking toward the\nsimplification of the federal\ngovernment, and the reduction\nof the expense. The Hoover com\nmission has reported its recom- u\nmendations. It is now up to con\ngress to enact those recom\nmendations into law, but to do\nso means reducing congres\nsional patronage, and that con\ngress will not do unless it is i\nforced by a vigorous demand on\nthe part of the voters.\nThe' California state chamber of\ncommerce now is promoting the\nidea of a commission to do foi*\nCalifornia what the Hoover com\nmission did lor the federal gov\nerment. It wants recommenda\ntions lor the organization of the\nstate's administrative branch; it\nwants to remove the needless der\npartments and bureaus, and the\nneedless employees on the state'*\npayrolls. It wants, also, to so sim\nplify the state government; to re\nmove overlapping jurisdiction and\nauthority, that it will be easier for\nits citizens to do business with the\nstate government, and with each\nother.\nIt is a worthy idea, and one that\nweU could be promoted in prac\ntically every state, and in every\nunit of government in all states.\nThere would be a minimum num\nber of branches in every state,\ncounty or city government. There\nwould be but few cases in which\nmeans of simplification' could no(\nbe found, or in which considerable\nexpense items could not be elimi c\nnated. They would not be thq\nHoover commission findings of\nbu$\nthey could be proportionately large.\nJust as the management of\nbusiness does not see savings\nand improvements because of\ntoo-close familiarity with pre-\nseat processes, so the executive j?\nbranch of a government will\nnot see the needed, or desirable, I\nchanges in the executive branch i.\nof a government which they are\ndirecting. As in the esse of the\nHoover commission, it needs\nwell-qualified outsiders work-\ning with a select group of in\nsiders to see possible changes,\nand make the necessary recom-\nmendations.\nThe commission is the first step,,\nThe recommendations, after care\nful study, is the second step. The,\nthird, dnd probably the hardest,\nstep is the enactment into law of\nthe recommendations. No matter\nwhether the legislative body be\na state l\u00e9gislature, a county board\nof supervisors, or a city council,\nall will need a constant and per\nsistent demand on the part of the\nvoters, for the enactment into law\nof these recommendations.\nScarcely a day, never a week,\npasses, when congress is in ses\nsion, that' some member of the\nhouse or senate does not propose\nsomething new for which to spend\nthe taxpayers' money. If they were\n'as interested in saving as in spend\ning, the recommendations of the*\nHoover commission would have at\ntracted their attention more quick\nly. That report shows how to save\nbillions in the administration of the\ngovernment, and, at th\u00e9 same time,\u00ab\nprovide more efficiency.\nt\nHill Proprietary Steelworks told a'\nreporter his company is exporting\nsteel to England at the request ot\nthe Australian government.\nNew South Wales Minister for\nTransport Maurice O'Sullivan saya\nhis government has to buy Japa\nnese steel for railroad building. He\ntold newsmen Japanese steel will\ncost about- $156 aganist about $54\nfor Australian steel.","height":"25845","width":"20256"}}
